# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-jacob-miller
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] Miller was born in Baltimore, Maryland, the eldest of nine children of George W. and Harriet J.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] Miller's father was a merchant and tavern keeper in central Baltimore, and also had a farm in Hawkins Point.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] Miller attended a private school in Baltimore, John D.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] Craig's Academy, but did not receive formal art instruction there.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] He may have received his first lessons in art from Thomas Sully.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] In 1832, with the financial support of his family and art patrons in Baltimore, Miller traveled to Paris to study art.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] He was admitted as an auditor to life drawing classes at the École des Beaux-Arts, and copied paintings in the collections of the Louvre.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] In 1833, he traveled to Italy, visiting Bologna, Florence, and Venice before settling in Rome, where he studied at the English Life School.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] During his travels in Europe, he became friends with the Danish sculptor Bertel Thorwaldsen and studied with the French painter Horace Vernet.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] He returned to Baltimore in 1834, where he opened a downtown studio and advertised himself as a painter of portraits and Old Master copies.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] Professional and financial difficulties may have prompted his decision to move to New Orleans in 1837.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] The city was a relatively open market for artists, and Miller quickly established a studio on Chartes Street and began receiving orders for portraits.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] It was in his studio that he met the Scottish aristocrat and adventurer, Sir William Drummond Stewart.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] Stewart hired Miller to accompany him and record his hunting journey to the Rocky Mountains.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] That same year, along with representatives of the American Fur Company, they ventured as far as Fort William and Green River.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] After returning to New Orleans later that year, Miller started working up his sketches in watercolors and oils.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] The scenes and incidents of the hunting journey were the foundation of a series of paintings documenting Native Americans of the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] In July 1838 Miller was able to arrange an exhibition in New Orleans.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] In October 1840 he traveled with his paintings to Stewart's Murthly Castle in Scotland, where a collection of his commissioned work was ultimately hung.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] After spending a year in Scotland and another in London, Miller returned to Baltimore in April 1842.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/alfred-jacob-miller] He established himself as an acknowledged portrait artist in the city.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The **American Fur Company** (**AFC**) was a prominent American company that sold furs, skins, and buffalo robes.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] It was founded in 1808 by John Jacob Astor, a German immigrant to the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] During its heyday in the early 19th century, the company dominated the American fur trade.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The company went bankrupt in 1842 and was dissolved in 1847.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] During the 18th century, furs had become a major commodity in Europe, and Indigenous people in North America became a major supplier.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Several British companies, most notably the North West Company (NWC) and the Hudson's Bay Company, competed against Astor and capitalized on the lucrative trade in furs.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Astor used a variety of commercial strategies to become one of the first trusts in American business and a major competitor to the British commercial dominance in North American fur trade.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Expanding into many former British fur-trapping regions and trade routes, the company grew to monopolize the fur trade in the United States by 1830, and became one of the largest and wealthiest businesses in the country.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Astor planned for several companies to function across the Great Lakes, the Great Plains and the Oregon Country to gain control of the North American fur trade.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Comparatively inexpensive manufactured goods were to be shipped to commercial stations for trade with various Indigenous nations for fur pelts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The sizable number of furs collected were then to be brought to the port of Canton, as pelts were in high demand in the Qing Empire.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Chinese products were, in turn, to be purchased for resale throughout Europe and the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] A beneficial agreement with the Russian-American Company was also planned through the regular supply of provisions for posts in Russian America.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] This was planned in part to prevent the rival Montreal based NWC to gain a presence along the Pacific Coast, a prospect neither the Russian colonial authorities nor Astor favored.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Demand for furs in Europe began to decline during the early 19th century, leading to the stagnation of the fur trade by the mid-19th century.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Astor left his company in 1830, the company declared bankruptcy in 1842, and the American Fur Company ultimately ceased trading in 1847.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] advocated for trade posts on the Pacific Coast, influencing Astor's decision to establish the PFC.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Before John Jacob Astor founded his enterprise in the Oregon Country, European descendants throughout previous decades had suggested creating trade stations along the Pacific Coast.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Peter Pond, an active American fur trader, offered maps of his explorations in modern Alberta, Saskatchewan and the Northwest Territories to both the United States Congress and to Henry Hamilton, Lieutenant Governor of Quebec in 1785.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] While it has been conjectured that Pond wanted funding from the Americans to explore the Pacific Coast for the Northwest Passage, there is no documentation of this and it is more likely that he had sent a copy of the map to Congress due to personal pride.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Pond later became a founding member of the North West Company (NWC) and continued to trade in modern Alberta.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] In time Pond had an influence upon Alexander Mackenzie, who later crossed the North American continent.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] In 1802, Mackenzie promoted a plan form the "Fishery and Fur Company" to the British government.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] In it he called for "a supreme Civil & Military Establishment" on Nootka Island, with two additional posts located on the Columbia River and another in the Alexander Archipelago.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Additionally this plan was formed to bypass the three major British monopolies at the time, the Hudson's Bay Company, the South Sea Company and the East India Company for access the Chinese markets.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] However the British government turned down the offer, leaving the NWC to pursue MacKenzie's plans alone.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Another likely influence upon Astor was a longtime friend, Alexander Henry.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] At times Henry mused at the potential of the western coast.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Forming establishments on the Pacific shoreline to harness the economic potential would be "my favorite plan" as Henry described in a letter to a New York merchant.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] It is likely that these considerations were discussed with Astor during his visits to Montreal and the Beaver Club.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Despite not originating the idea to create a venture on the Pacific coast, Astor's "ability to combine and use the ideas of other men" allowed him to pursue the idea.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Astor joined in on two NWC voyages charted to sail to the Qing Empire during the 1790s.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] These were done with American vessels to bypass British commercial law, which at the time prohibited any company besides the East India Company from commerce with China.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] These were financially profitable ventures, enough so that Astor offered to become the NWC agent for all shipments of furs destined for Guangzhou.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] However Alexander Mackenzie denied his offer, making Astor consider financing voyages to China without the Canadian traders.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Now a fully independent international merchant, Astor began to fund trading voyages to China along with several partners.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Cargoes often amounted to $150,000 (equivalent to about $4 million in 2025) in such as otter and beaver pelts, in addition to needed specie.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Astor ordered the construction of the *Beaver* in 1803 to expand his trade fleet.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] By the early 1800s the Chicago area was already a large center for the fur trade.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The city was largely occupied by soldiers stationed at Fort Dearborn and fur traders in small camps.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Prior to the War of 1812 the British maintained control of the area.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] However, in 1811 John Jacob Astor's American Fur Company began to lay the foundation to move into the area.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] This foundation began with a partnership between the American Fur Company and two British companies that supplied trade goods to the Chicago area.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The terms of this arrangement were such that the partnership would last for five years or until the American government prohibited the use of foreign capital in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] This partnership was short lived as after the War of 1812 the United States government banned foreign investors from entering the United States and engaging in trade with Native Americans.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Congress passed this law at the urging of John Jacob Astor with the caveat that a special exemption to this law could be granted exclusively by the president.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Later this power would be given to Native American tribes and some territorial officials.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] One years time was enough that John Jacob Astor and the American Fur Company has sufficient connections in the area to fill the void left by the banning of the British Companies that formerly held control of the Chicago fur trade.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] By 1808, Astor had established "an international empire that mixed furs, teas, and silks and penetrated markets on three continents." He began to court diplomatic and government support of a fur trading venture to be established on the Pacific shore in the same year.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] In correspondence with the Mayor of New York City, DeWitt Clinton, Astor explained that a state charter would offer a particular level of formal sanction needed in the venture.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] He in turn requested the Federal government grant his operations military support to defend against Indians and control these new markets.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The bold proposals were not given official sanction however, making Astor to continue to promote his ideas among prominent governmental agents.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] President Thomas Jefferson was contacted by the ambitious merchant as well.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Once the pelts were collected from the extensive outposts they were to be loaded and shipped aboard ships owned by Astor to the Chinese port of Guangzhou, where furs were sold for impressive profits.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Chinese products like porcelain, nankeens and tea were to be purchased; with the ships then to cross the Indian Ocean and head for European and American markets to sell the Chinese wares.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] To begin his plans of a chain of trading stations spread across the Rocky Mountains to the Pacific Northwest, Astor incorporated the AFC subsidiary, the Pacific Fur Company.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Astor and the partners met in New York on 23 June 1810 and signed the Pacific Fur Company's provisional agreement.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The fellow partners were former NWC men, being Alexander McKay, Duncan McDougall, and Donald Mackenzie.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The chief representative of Astor in the daily operations was Wilson Price Hunt, a St.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Louis businessman with no outback experience.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] From the outpost on the Columbia, Astor hoped to gain a commercial foothold in Russian America and China.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] In particular, the ongoing supply issues faced by the Russian-American Company were seen as a means to gain yet more furs.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Cargo ships en route from the Columbia were planned to then sail north for Russian America to bring much needed provisions.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] By cooperating with Russian colonial authorities to strengthen their material presence in Russian America, it was hoped by Astor to stop the NWC or any other British presence to be established upon the Pacific Coast.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] A tentative agreement for merchant vessels owned by Astor to ship furs gathered in Russian America into the Qing Empire was signed in 1812.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] While intended to gain control of the regional fur trade, the Pacific Fur Company floundered in the War of 1812.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The possibility of an occupation by the Royal Navy forced the sale of all company assets across the Oregon Country.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] This was formalized on 23 October 1813 with the raising of the Union Jack at Fort Astoria.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] On 30 November HMS *Racoon* arrived at the Columbia River and in honor of George III of the United Kingdom, Fort Astoria was renamed Fort George.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] After the forced merger in 1821 of the North West Company into their long time rivals, the Hudson's Bay Company, in a short time the HBC controlled the majority of the fur trade across the Pacific Northwest.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The South West Company handled the Midwestern and Southwestern fur trade.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] In the Midwest, it also competed with regional companies along the upper Missouri, upper Mississippi, Platte rivers and as far south as New Mexico.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] These competitors were mostly companies based in Saint Louis, Missouri, which were active in the fur trade as well as in trade of general merchandise, and which were typically founded and led by French colonial families, such as Pratte, Chouteau, Cabanne and Ceran St.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Vrain amongst the most prominent, both before and after the Louisiana Purchase or Astor setting up his company.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Competition in the wilderness areas between men of the companies sometimes erupted into physical violence and outright attacks.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] In 1834, the American Fur Company sold its Western Division to Bernard Pratte and Pierre Chouteau Jr., with whom they had been already cooperating, with the latter continuing the business as Pratte, Chouteau & Company.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] For a time, it seemed that the company had been destroyed but, following the war, the United States passed a law excluding foreign traders from operating on U.S. territory.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] This freed the American Fur Company from having to compete with the Canadian and British companies, particularly along the borders around the Great Lakes and in the West.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The AFC competed fiercely among American companies to establish a monopoly in the Great Lakes region and the Midwest.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] In the 1820s the AFC expanded its monopoly into the Great Plains and the Rocky Mountains, dominating the fur trade in what became Montana by the mid-1830s.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] To achieve control of the industry, the company bought out or beat out many smaller competitors, like the Rocky Mountain Fur Company.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] By 1830, the AFC had nearly complete control of the fur trade in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The company's time at the top of America's business world was short-lived.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Sensing the eventual decline of fur's popularity in fashion, John Jacob Astor withdrew from the company in 1834.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The company split into smaller entities like the Pacific Fur Company.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The Northern Division of the midwestern outfit continued to be called the American Fur Company and was led by Ramsay Crooks.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] To cut down on expenses, it began closing many of its trading posts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Through the 1830s, competition began to resurface.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] At the same time, the availability of furs in the Midwest declined.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] During this period, the Hudson's Bay Company began an effort to destroy the American fur companies from its Columbia District headquarters at Fort Vancouver.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] By depleting furs in the Snake River country and underselling the American Fur Company at the annual Rocky Mountain Rendezvous, the HBC effectively ruined American fur trading efforts in the Rocky Mountains.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] By the 1840s, silk was replacing fur for hats as the clothing fashion in Europe.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The company was unable to cope with all these factors.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Despite efforts to increase profits by diversifying into other industries like lead mining, the American Fur Company folded.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The assets of the company were split into several smaller operations, most of which failed by the 1850s.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] In 1834, John Jacob Astor sold his interest on the river to replace the old fur company.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] He invested his fortune in real estate on Manhattan Island, New York, and became the wealthiest man in America.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] After 1840, the business of the American Fur Company declined.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] During its heyday, the American Fur Company was one of the largest enterprises in the United States and held a total monopoly of the lucrative fur trade in the young nation by the 1820s.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Through his profits from the company, John Jacob Astor made numerous, lucrative land investments and became the richest man in the world and the first multi-millionaire in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The German-born Astor is ranked as the eighteenth-wealthiest person of all time, and the eighth to create his fortune in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] He used part of his fortune to found the Astor Library in New York City.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Later it merged with the Lenox Library to form the New York Public Library.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] On the frontier, the American Fur Company opened the way for the settlement and economic development of the Midwestern and Western United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Mountain men working for the company improved Native American trails and carved others that led settlers into the West.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] Many cities in the Midwest and West, such as Fort Benton, Montana, and Astoria, Oregon developed around American Fur Company trading posts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/american-fur-company] The company played a major role in the development and expansion of the young United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The *Cyclopædia* included the names of over 20,000 native and adopted citizens of the United States, including living persons.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Also included were the names of several thousand citizens of all the other countries of North and South America.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The aim was to embrace all noteworthy persons of the New World.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The work also contained the names of nearly 1,000 people of foreign birth who were closely identified with American history.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The *Cyclopædia* was illustrated with about sixty full-page portraits supplemented by some 1,500 smaller vignette portraits accompanied by facsimile autographs, and also several hundred views of birthplaces, residences, monuments, and tombs famous in history.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] None of the articles are signed either with names or with initials.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The clue to authorship is obtained, when obtained at all, through a list of contributors and their contributions arranged alphabetically as to contributors.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] One reviewer found this a rather inconvenient method, complaining that the finding of the author of a particular sketch often involved a voyage of discovery through the entire list.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] These lists are searched in vain, however, for the authors of many sketches, including the one of President Grover Cleveland.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The first discovery of these fictitious biographies was in 1919 by John Hendley Barnhart, when he identified and reprinted, with commentary, 14 biographical sketches of supposed European botanists who had come to the New World to study in Latin America.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] By 1939, 47 fictitious biographies had been discovered, though only the letters H and V had been systematically investigated.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The status of fictitious biographies in *Appletons' Cyclopædia* was also assessed by Margaret Castle Schindler of Goucher College in 1937.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] While three of the fictitious biographies (those of Joseph Dombey, Rafael Ferrer and Huet de Navarre) *were* about a real person, most of the details in these biographies were fictitious.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Joseph Cantillion identified the author of "phantom Jesuit" articles as William Christian Tenner: he identified 43 wholly fictitious subjects in this genre, as well as a mostly fictitious biography of Ferrer, and presented a list of 94 fictitious entries.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Dobson suggests Hermann Ritter, who appears as the source of "Articles on South and Central Americans" beginning with volume III, as another likely author of the fictitious articles.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Dobson notes that the first two volumes, where Juan G.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Puron appears in this role, are practically free of fictitious articles, although he identified an article on "Dávila, Nepomuceno" as suspicious, while "Chel-Ab-Ku-Kil", "Chignavitcelut" and "Oxiquieb Chiguaihue" are also listed as suspicious.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] In Dobson's 1993 study of Appleton's, he found four articles in the letter I to be fictitious.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Articles on "Ingulf von Köln, Rudolf" (listed as suspicious by Dobson) and "Zénon de Rouvroy, Charles-Albert" (sometimes mentioned as "de Rouvroy, Charles-Albert Zénon") were found by Williams in 2021 to be fictitious.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] Contributors to *Appletons' Cyclopædia* were free to suggest new subjects and were paid according to the length of the article, with articles only being checked for form by the editorial staff.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] While conceding that *Appletons' Cyclopædia* was a "valuable and authoritative work", and that her results should not reflect on the many authentic articles, Schindler noted that articles on Latin American subjects should be used cautiously until verified against other sources.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The first edition of the *Cyclopædia* was published between 1887 and 1889 by D.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The general editors were James Grant Wilson and John Fiske; the managing editor from 1886 to 1888 was Rossiter Johnson.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] A seventh volume, containing an appendix and supplementary lists, and thematic indexes to the whole work, was issued in 1901.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/appletons-cyclopædia-of-american-biography] The *Cyclopædia* was republished, uncorrected, by the Gale Research Company in 1968.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The **Archives of American Art** is the largest collection of primary resources documenting the history of the visual arts in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] More than 20 million items of original material are housed in the Archives' research centers in Washington, D.C., and New York City.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] As a research center within the Smithsonian Institution, the Archives houses materials related to a variety of American visual art and artists.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] All regions of the country and numerous eras and art movements are represented.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Among the significant artists represented in its collection are Jackson Pollock, Lee Krasner, Marcel Breuer, Rockwell Kent, John Singer Sargent, Winslow Homer, John Trumbull, and Alexander Calder.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] In addition to the papers of artists, the Archives collects documentary material from art galleries, art dealers, and art collectors.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] It also houses a collection of over 2,000 art-related oral history interviews, and publishes a bi-yearly publication, the *Archives of American Art Journal*, which showcases collections within the Archives.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The Archives of American Art was founded in Detroit in 1954 by then Director of the Detroit Institute of Arts, Edgar Preston Richardson, and art collector Lawrence A.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The first archivist was Arline Custer, the librarian of the Detroit Institute of Arts Research Library.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Concerned about the lack of material relating to American art, Richardson and Fleischman organized the Archives of American Art with the support of scholars and businessmen.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Their intention was to collect materials related to American artists, art dealers, institutions and writers, and to allow scholars and writers to access the holdings.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] In 1970 the Archives became part of the Smithsonian Institution, moving its processing center and storage facility from Detroit to the Old Patent Office Building in Washington, D.C.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Currently, the collection and offices are located at the Victor Building, on 9th Street NW, only a few blocks away from the Old Patent Office Building.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Every year the Archives honors individual contributions to the American art community with the *Archives of American Art Medal* and art historians with the *Lawrence A.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Fleischman Award for Scholarly Excellence in the Field of American Art History*.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] These awards are presented at the Archives' annual benefit and have been rewarded to Mark di Suvero, Chuck Close, John Wilmerding and others.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] In 2011, the Archives of American Art became the first Smithsonian business unit to work directly with Wikipedia through the Wikipedia Galleries, Libraries, and Museums project, starting by appointing the first Smithsonian Wikipedian in Residence, Sarah Stierch.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Today's affiliates consist of the DeYoung, Boston Public Library, the Amon Carter Museum and The Huntington Library.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The Archives also offers microfilm for interlibrary loan at no charge.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Microfilm is no longer being produced at the Archives as it has been superseded by digitization.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] With funding from the Terra Foundation for American Art Digitization Program, the Archives has fully digitized numerous collections, which are accessible on their website.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] In April, 2011, the Archives received a second Terra grant of $3 million to fund another five years of digitization and technological developments, which began in 2005 with a $3.6 million grant from Terra.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The Archives relies heavily on grants and private donations to fund the archival processing and care of collections.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] In 2009 the Archives received a $213,315 grant from the Leon Levy Foundation to process the André Emmerich Gallery records and a $100,000 gift from the Kress Foundation to complete the digitization of the Jacques Seligmann & Company records.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] In 2009 the Archives acquired 88 collections totaling 717 linear feet.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The Archives holds a unique collection of material from notable artists, dealers, critics and collectors.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] While papers and documents make up a large portion of the Archives, more unique objects have been acquired over the years.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] These include a bird nest and a Kewpie doll from the collection of artist Joseph Cornell; painter George Luks' death mask; and a cast iron model car that belonged to Franz Kline.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The earliest letter in the collection was written by John Smibert in 1743, in which Smibert describes to his dealer his theories about the future of art in America.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The Archives maintain over 50 paper collections of African American artists.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Subjects covered in these personal papers include the expatriate experience, racism within the arts, and the Federal Art Project.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The collection includes the sketchbooks of Palmer Hayden, Horace Pippin's illustrated journal of his military service during World War I, and photographs of Alma Thomas.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Other notable collections represent Charles Alston, Hughie Lee-Smith, Jacob Lawrence, Romare Bearden and Henry Ossawa Tanner.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Over 100 individuals and organizations are represented in the Archives' Latin American art collection.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Topics range from Mexican muralism to Surrealism, New Deal art patronage and the Chicano Movement.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Notable collections include the diary of Carlos Lopez, the sketchbooks of Emilio Sanchez, source material for Mel Ramos and research materials from Esther McCoy relating to Mexican architecture.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] They also maintain oral histories starting in 1964.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] In 1989–1996, with additions in 2007 and 2017, Boris Mirski's family donated the records of the Boris Mirski Gallery (1944–1979) to the Archives.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Mirski's Gallery showed avant-garde art, including work in the New York and international modern art styles as well as non-western art.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] But it was best known for being a major birthing ground for American Figurative Expressionism as a whole, and Boston Expressionism, in particular, especially for mid-century Jewish American artists.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Several key figures in Boston Expressionism, linked to Mirski, have also given oral history interviews to the Archives, including Hyman Bloom, David Aronson, Jack Levine, Marianna Pineda, Arthur Polonsky and Karl Zerbe.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] In 2007, gallery owner Leo Castelli's family donated his papers to the Archives.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] It took three years to organize the collection of more than 400 linear feet.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The collection consists of the sales of every artwork sold by the gallery during Castelli's lifetime, published reviews of the gallery's exhibits, photographs, and correspondence with the many artists he represented, which included, among others, Roy Lichtenstein, Ellsworth Kelly, and Andy Warhol.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Painter, author and illustrator Rockwell Kent donated his collection in 1969.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] It contained over 60,000 letters, notes, sketches, manuscripts, photographs and business records covering 70 years.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] One month later his house burned to the ground and Kent was quoted as stating that he had wished he had donated the entire house to the Archives.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] In 1958, the Archives of American Art started an oral history program with base support from the Ford Foundation and continued with support from New York State Council on the Arts, Pew Charitable Trust, the Mark Rothko Foundation, and the Pasadena Art Alliance.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Today the Archives houses nearly 2,000 oral history interviews relating to American art.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The program continues today with funding from the Terra Foundation of American Art, the Brown Foundation of Houston, the Widgeon Point Charitable Foundation, the Art Dealers Association of America.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Laitman Documentation Project for Craft and Decorative Arts in America enabling over 150 interviews with American craft artists.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The Archives mounts rotating exhibitions of its collections at the Lawrence A.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Reynolds Center for American Art and Portraiture in Washington, D.C.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Exhibitions have included *Of the Moment: A Video Sampler from the Archives of American Art*, and *Hard Times, 1929–1939*, which examined the Great Depression's impact on American artists.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] In 2012, the Archives celebrated the centennial birth of Jackson Pollock with an exhibition of Pollock's archives and artwork.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] The Archives of American Art is one of nine research centers of the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] It is managed by a director, nominated by a board of trustees.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Anne Helmreich was appointed the new director in 2023.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/archives-of-american-art] Governance includes an executive committee, a council, and emeriti members.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The land that is present-day Baltimore was once used as hunting ground by Paleo-Indians.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In the early 1600s, the Susquehannock began to hunt there.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] People from the Province of Maryland established the Port of Baltimore in 1706 to support the tobacco trade with Europe and established the Town of Baltimore in 1729.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Battle of Baltimore was pivotal during the War of 1812, culminating in the British bombardment of Fort McHenry, during which Francis Scott Key wrote a poem that became "The Star-Spangled Banner", which was designated as the national anthem in 1931.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] During the Pratt Street Riot of 1861, the city was the site of some of the earliest violence associated with the American Civil War.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore and Ohio Railroad, the nation's oldest, was built in 1830 and reinforced Baltimore's status as a transportation hub, giving producers in the Midwest and Appalachia access to the city's port.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore's Inner Harbor was the second-leading port of entry for immigrants to the U.S. after New York's Ellis Island, making Baltimore a major manufacturing center.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] After a decline in heavy industry and restructuring of the rail industry, Baltimore has shifted to a service-oriented economy.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Johns Hopkins Hospital and University are now the city's top employers.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is also home to the Baltimore Orioles of Major League Baseball and the Baltimore Ravens of the National Football League.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] It is ranked as a Gamma− world city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The city is home to some of the earliest National Register Historic Districts in the nation, including Fell's Point, Federal Hill, and Mount Vernon.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore has more public statues and monuments per capita than any other city in the U.S.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Nearly one third of the buildings (over 65,000) are designated as historic in the National Register, more than any other U.S. city.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore has 66 National Register Historic Districts and 33 local historic districts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The city is named after Cecil Calvert, 2nd Baron Baltimore, an English politician and lawyer who was a founding proprietor of the Province of Maryland.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Calverts took the title Barons Baltimore from Baltimore Manor, an estate they were granted by the Crown in County Longford as part of the plantations of Ireland.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is an anglicization of *Baile an Tí Mhóir*, meaning "town of the big house" in Irish.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore area was inhabited by Native Americans since at least the 10th millennium BC, when Paleo-Indians first settled in the region.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] One Paleo-Indian site and several Archaic period and Woodland period archaeological sites have been identified in Baltimore, including four from the Late Woodland period.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In December 2021, several Woodland period Native American artifacts were found in Herring Run Park in northeast Baltimore, dating 5,000 to 9,000 years ago.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The finding followed a period of dormancy in Baltimore City archaeological findings which had persisted since the 1980s.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] During the Late Woodland period, the archaeological culture known as the Potomac Creek complex resided in the area from Baltimore south to the Rappahannock River in present-day Virginia.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In the early 1600s, the immediate Baltimore vicinity was sparsely populated, if at all, by Native Americans.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore County area northward was used as hunting grounds by the Susquehannock living in the lower Susquehanna River valley.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] This Iroquoian-speaking people "controlled all of the upper tributaries of the Chesapeake" but "refrained from much contact with Powhatan in the Potomac region" and south into Virginia.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Pressured by the Susquehannock, the Piscataway tribe, an Algonquian-speaking people, stayed well south of the Baltimore area and inhabited primarily the north bank of the Potomac River in what are now Charles and southern Prince George's counties in the coastal areas south of the Fall Line.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] European colonization of Maryland began in earnest with the arrival of the merchant ship *The Ark* carrying 140 colonists at St.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Clement's Island in the Potomac River on March 25, 1634.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Europeans then began to settle the area further north, in what is now Baltimore County.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Since Maryland was a colony, Baltimore's streets were named to show loyalty to the mother country, e.g.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] King, Queen, King George and Caroline streets.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The original county seat, known today as Old Baltimore, was located on Bush River within the present-day Aberdeen Proving Ground.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The colonists engaged in sporadic warfare with the Susquehannock, whose numbers dwindled primarily from new infectious diseases, such as smallpox, endemic among the Europeans.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 1661, David Jones claimed the area known today as Jonestown on the east bank of the Jones Falls stream.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The colonial General Assembly of Maryland created the Port of Baltimore at old Whetstone Point, now Locust Point, in 1706 for the tobacco trade.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Town of Baltimore, on the west side of the Jones Falls, was founded on August 8, 1729, when the Governor of Maryland signed an act allowing "the building of a Town on the North side of the Patapsco River".
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Surveyors began laying out the town on January 12, 1730.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] By 1752 the town had just 27 homes, including a church and two taverns.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Jonestown and Fells Point had been settled to the east.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The three settlements, covering 60 acres (24 ha), became a commercial hub, and in 1768 were designated as the county seat.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The first printing press was introduced to the city in 1765 by Nicholas Hasselbach, whose equipment was later used in the printing of Baltimore's first newspapers, *The Maryland Journal* and *The Baltimore Advertiser*, first published by William Goddard in 1773.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore grew swiftly in the 18th century, its plantations producing grain and tobacco for sugar-producing colonies in the Caribbean.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The profit from sugar encouraged the cultivation of cane in the Caribbean and the importation of food by planters there.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Since Baltimore was the county seat, a courthouse was built in 1768 to serve both the city and county.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Its square was a center of community meetings and discussions.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore established its public market system in 1763.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Lexington Market, founded in 1782, is one of the oldest continuously operating public markets in the United States today.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Lexington Market was also a center of slave trading.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Enslaved Black people were sold at numerous sites through the downtown area, with sales advertised in *The Baltimore Sun*.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Both tobacco and sugar cane were labor-intensive crops.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 1774, Baltimore established the first post office system in what became the United States, and the first water company chartered in the newly independent nation, Baltimore Water Company, 1792.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore played a part in the American Revolution.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] City leaders such as Jonathan Plowman Jr. led many residents to resist British taxes, and merchants signed agreements refusing to trade with Britain.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Second Continental Congress met in the Henry Fite House from December 1776 to February 1777, effectively making the city the capital of the United States during this period.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore, Jonestown, and Fells Point were incorporated as the City of Baltimore in 1796–1797.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The city remained a part of surrounding Baltimore County and continued to serve as its county seat from 1768 to 1851, after which it became an independent city.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The British bombardment of Baltimore in 1814 inspired the U.S. national anthem, "The Star-Spangled Banner", and the construction of the Battle Monument, which became the city's official emblem.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] A distinctive local culture started to take shape, and a unique skyline peppered with churches and monuments developed.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore acquired its moniker "The Monumental City" after an 1827 visit to Baltimore by President John Quincy Adams.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore pioneered the use of gas lighting in 1816, and its population grew rapidly in the following decades, with concomitant development of culture and infrastructure.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The construction of the federally funded National Road, which later became part of U.S.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Route 40, and the private Baltimore and Ohio Railroad (B. & O.) made Baltimore a major shipping and manufacturing center by linking the city with major markets in the Midwest.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] By 1820 its population had reached 60,000, and its economy had shifted from its base in tobacco plantations to sawmilling, shipbuilding, and textile production.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] These industries benefited from war but successfully shifted into infrastructure development during peacetime.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore had one of the worst riots of the antebellum South in 1835, when bad investments led to the Baltimore bank riot.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] It was these riots that led to the city being nicknamed "Mobtown".
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Soon after the city created the world's first dental college, the Baltimore College of Dental Surgery, in 1840, and shared in the world's first telegraph line, between Baltimore and Washington, D.C., in 1844.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Maryland, a slave state with limited popular support for secession, especially in the three counties of Southern Maryland, remained part of the Union during the American Civil War, following the 55–12 vote by the Maryland General Assembly against secession.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In February 1861, a plot in Baltimore to assassinate President-elect Abraham Lincoln was foiled by agents of the Pinkerton National Detective Agency.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Lincoln was able to pass through the city unnoticed, and arrived in Washington to be inaugurated a little more than a week later.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Later, the Union's strategic occupation of the city in 1861 ensured Maryland would not further consider secession.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Union's capital of Washington, D.C. was well-situated to impede Baltimore and Maryland's communication or commerce with the Confederacy.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore experienced some of the first casualties of the Civil War on April 19, 1861, when Union Army soldiers en route from President Street Station to Camden Yards clashed with a secessionist mob in the Pratt Street riot.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In the midst of the Long Depression that followed the Panic of 1873, the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad company attempted to lower its workers' wages, leading to strikes and riots in the city and beyond.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Strikers clashed with the National Guard, leaving 10 dead and 25 wounded. settlement movement work in Baltimore began in 1893 with the founding of the Lawrence House on West Lombard Street.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] On February 7, 1904, the Great Baltimore Fire destroyed more than 1,500 buildings and left over 70 blocks of downtown Baltimore burned to the ground.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Damage was estimated at $150 million in 1904 dollars.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Rebuilding over the following years included improvements in firefighting equipment standards.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 1910, Baltimore enacted a residential segregation ordinance that restricted African-Americans from moving into majority-White blocks, and White residents from moving into majority-Black blocks.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] It was the first ordinance of its kind in the United States and became a model for similar laws in other southern cities, although the U.S.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Supreme Court later ruled such ordinances unconstitutional in *Buchanan v.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore expanded through annexations until 1918, when it acquired portions of Baltimore County and Anne Arundel County.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] A 1948 state constitutional amendment required a local vote in any area proposed for annexation, effectively preventing further expansion of the city's boundaries.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] During the mid-20th century, migration from the Deep South and white suburbanization changed the city's demographics: the Black share of the population rose from 23.8% in 1950 to 46.4% in 1970.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore riot of 1968 followed the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. on April 4, 1968.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Public order was not restored until April 12, and National Guard and federal troops were sent into the city.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 1974, the city again faced major disruption when teachers, municipal workers, and police officers went on strike.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] By the early 1970s, the Inner Harbor had declined into an area of abandoned warehouses.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Redevelopment began with projects such as the Maryland Science Center in 1976, the Baltimore World Trade Center in 1977, and the Baltimore Convention Center in 1979.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Harborplace opened in 1980, followed by the National Aquarium and the Baltimore Museum of Industry in 1981.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 1992, the Baltimore Orioles moved from Memorial Stadium to Oriole Park at Camden Yards, near the Inner Harbor.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore Ravens later moved into M&T Bank Stadium, next to Camden Yards, in 1998.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore has seen the reopening of the Hippodrome Theatre in 2004, the opening of the Reginald F.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Lewis Museum of Maryland African American History & Culture in 2005, and the establishment of the National Slavic Museum in 2012.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In April 2012, Johns Hopkins dedicated a $1.1 billion expansion of the Johns Hopkins Hospital, among the largest medical complexes in the United States, comprising the Sheikh Zayed Cardiovascular and Critical Care Tower and the Charlotte R.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In September 2016, the Baltimore City Council approved a $660 million bond deal for the $5.5 billion Port Covington redevelopment project championed by Under Armour founder Kevin Plank and his real estate company Sagamore Development.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Port Covington surpassed the Harbor Point development as the largest tax-increment financing deal in Baltimore's history and among the largest urban redevelopment projects in the country.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The waterfront development includes a new headquarters for Under Armour along with shops, housing, offices, and manufacturing space.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In the early hours of March 26, 2024, the city's 1.6-mile (2.6 km) Francis Scott Key Bridge, which constituted a southeast portion of the Baltimore Beltway, was struck by a container ship and completely collapsed.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] A major rescue operation was launched with US authorities attempting to rescue people in the water.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Eight construction workers, who were working on the bridge at the time, fell into the Patapsco River.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Two people were rescued from the water, and the bodies of the remaining six were all found by May 7.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Replacement of the bridge was estimated in May 2024 at a cost approaching $2 billion for a fall 2028 completion.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is in north-central Maryland on the Patapsco River, close to where it empties into the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is located on the fall line between the Piedmont Plateau and the Atlantic coastal plain, which divides Baltimore into "lower city" and "upper city".
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore's elevation ranges from sea level at the harbor to 480 feet (150 m) in the northwest corner near Pimlico.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In the 2010 census, Baltimore has a total area of 92.1 square miles (239 km2), of which 80.9 sq mi (210 km2) is land and 11.1 sq mi (29 km2) is water.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is almost entirely surrounded by Baltimore County, but is politically independent of it.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] It is bordered by Anne Arundel County to the south.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore exhibits examples from each period of architecture over more than two centuries, and work from architects such as Benjamin Latrobe, George A.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Frederick, John Russell Pope, Mies van der Rohe, and I.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is rich in architecturally significant buildings in a variety of styles.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore Basilica (1806–1821) is a neoclassical design by Benjamin Latrobe, and one of the oldest Catholic cathedrals in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 1813, Robert Cary Long Sr. built for Rembrandt Peale the first substantial structure in the United States designed expressly as a museum.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Restored, it is now the Municipal Museum of Baltimore, or popularly the Peale Museum.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Phoenix Shot Tower (1828), at 234.25 feet (71.40 m) tall, was the tallest building in the United States until the time of the Civil War, and is one of few remaining structures of its kind.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] It was constructed without the use of exterior scaffolding.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Hatfield in 1851, was the city's first iron-front building and was a model for a whole generation of downtown buildings.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Brown Memorial Presbyterian Church, built in 1870 in memory of financier George Brown, has stained glass windows by Louis Comfort Tiffany and has been called "one of the most significant buildings in this city, a treasure of art and architecture" by *Baltimore* magazine.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The 1845 Greek Revival-style Lloyd Street Synagogue is one of the oldest synagogues in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Johns Hopkins Hospital, designed by Lt.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Billings in 1876, was a considerable achievement for its day in functional arrangement and fireproofing.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Pei's World Trade Center (1977) is the tallest equilateral pentagonal building in the world at 405 feet (123 m) tall.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The streets of Baltimore are organized in a grid and spoke pattern, lined with tens of thousands of rowhouses whose mix of brick and formstone facings gives the city a distinct look; the latter was a technology patented in 1937 by Albert Knight.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] John Waters characterized formstone as "the polyester of brick".
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Developers began building entire neighborhoods of rowhouses in the mid-1790s, and the form became the dominant house type of the city early in the 19th century.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Oriole Park at Camden Yards is a Major League Baseball park, which opened in 1992 and was built as a retro style baseball park.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Along with the National Aquarium, Camden Yards have helped revive the Inner Harbor area from what once was an exclusively industrial district full of dilapidated warehouses into a bustling commercial district full of bars, restaurants, and retail establishments.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is commonly divided into nine geographic regions: North, Northeast, East, Southeast, South, Southwest, West, Northwest, and Central, each corresponding to a Baltimore Police Department district.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] I-83 and Charles Street to Hanover Street and Ritchie Highway serve as a rough east–west dividing line, while Eastern Avenue to Route 40 serves as a north–south divider; for the U.S.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Postal Service, Baltimore Street is the north–south dividing line.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] North Baltimore contains historic neighborhoods such as Govans, Roland Park, Guilford, Homeland, Hampden, Charles Village, and Mount Washington, as well as the Station North Arts and Entertainment District.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] South Baltimore and Southeast Baltimore include mixed residential, industrial, and waterfront neighborhoods such as Federal Hill, Locust Point, Fells Point, Canton, Highlandtown, Little Italy, and Greektown.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Landmarks in these areas include Fort McHenry, Patterson Park, the Highlandtown Arts District, and Johns Hopkins Bayview Medical Center.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Northeast Baltimore is largely residential and includes Morgan State University, Baltimore City College, the former site of Memorial Stadium, and Lake Montebello.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] East Baltimore includes Johns Hopkins Hospital, the Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine, and neighborhoods such as Armistead Gardens, Broadway East, Barclay, and McElderry Park.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Northwest Baltimore includes Pimlico Race Course, Sinai Hospital, the headquarters of the NAACP, and neighborhoods such as Pimlico, Mount Washington, Cheswolde, and Park Heights.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] West Baltimore includes the Old West Baltimore Historic District, historically a center of the city's Black community, as well as Coppin State University, Mondawmin Mall, and Edmondson Village.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Southwest Baltimore includes Pigtown, Carrollton Ridge, Ridgely's Delight, Leakin Park, and St.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is bordered by the following communities, all unincorporated census-designated places.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore has a humid subtropical (Köppen: *Cfa*) or oceanic (Trewartha: *Doak*) climate, with hot summers, cool winters, and a summer peak to annual precipitation.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is part of USDA plant hardiness zones 7b and 8a.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with a daily average in July of 80.7 °F (27.1 °C) and occasional late-day thunderstorms.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Spring and autumn are mild, with spring the wettest season by number of precipitation days.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Winters range from chilly to mild, with sporadic snowfall: January has a daily average of 35.8 °F (2.1 °C), though temperatures reach 50 °F (10 °C) quite often and can occasionally drop below 20 °F (−7 °C) when Arctic air masses affect the area.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] According to *Vox*, winters are warming faster than summers.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] A southeasterly bay breeze off the Chesapeake often occurs on summer afternoons; interacting with prevailing southwesterly winds and the city's urban heat island, it can exacerbate air quality.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In late summer and early autumn, hurricanes or their remnants may cause flooding in downtown Baltimore, despite the city being far removed from the typical coastal storm surge areas.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The average seasonal snowfall is 19 inches (48 cm).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] It varies greatly by year, with some seasons seeing only trace accumulations of snow, while others see several major Nor'easters.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Owing to lessened urban heat island (UHI) as compared to the city proper and distance from the moderating Chesapeake Bay, the outlying and inland parts of the Baltimore metro area are usually cooler, especially at night, than the city proper and the coastal towns.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Thus, in the northern and western suburbs, winter snowfall is more significant, and some areas average more than 30 in (76 cm) of snow per winter.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] It is common in winter for the rain-snow line to set up in the metro area, and freezing rain and sleet occur a few times some winters.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Like all of Maryland, Baltimore is at risk for increased impacts of climate change.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Historically, flooding has ruined houses and almost killed people, especially in lower income majority Black neighborhoods, and caused sewage backups, given the existing disrepair of Baltimore's water system.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Extreme temperatures have ranged from −7 °F (−22 °C), most recently on January 22, 1984, up to 108 °F (42 °C) on July 22, 2011.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] On average, temperatures of 100 °F (38 °C) or more occur on three days annually, 90 °F (32 °C) or more on 43 days, and there are nine days where the high fails to reach the freezing mark.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore reached a peak population of 949,708 at the 1950 U.S. census count.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In every ten-year census count since then, the city has lost population, with its 2020 census population at 585,708.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is the most populous independent city in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2020, Baltimore lost more population than any other major city in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The population increased for the first time in decades in 2024.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Gentrification has increased since the 2000 census, primarily in East Baltimore, downtown, and Central Baltimore, with 14.8% of census tracts having had income growth and home values appreciation at a rate higher than the city overall.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Many, but not all, gentrifying neighborhoods are predominantly white areas which have seen a turnover from lower income to higher income households.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] These areas represent either expansion of existing gentrified areas, or activity around the Inner Harbor, downtown, or the Johns Hopkins Homewood campus.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In some neighborhoods in East Baltimore, the Hispanic population has increased, while both the non-Hispanic white and non-Hispanic black populations have declined.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] After New York City, Baltimore was the second city in the United States to reach a population of 100,000.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] It was the second most-populous U.S. city from 1820 to 1850, and remained among the ten largest in every census through 1980.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] After World War II, the city's population approached one million before beginning its decline after the 1950 census.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In the 2010 census, Baltimore's population was 63.7% Black, 29.6% White (the largest ancestries being German, Italian, and Irish), 2.3% Asian, and 0.4% Native American and Alaska Native.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Across races, 4.2% of the population were of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin, most commonly Salvadoran and Mexican.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] As per the 2020 census, 8.1% of residents between 2016 and 2020 were foreign born persons.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Females made up 53.4% of the population.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The median age was 35 years old, with 22.4% under 18 years old, 65.8% from 18 to 64 years old, and 11.8% 65 or older.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore has a large Caribbean American population, with the largest groups being Jamaicans and Trinidadians.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore's Jamaican community is largely centered in the Park Heights neighborhood, but generations of immigrants have also lived in Southeast Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2005, approximately 30,778 people (6.5%) identified as gay, lesbian, or bisexual.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2012, same-sex marriage in Maryland was legalized, going into effect January 1, 2013.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Between 2016 and 2020, the median household income was $52,164 and the median income per capita was $32,699, compared to the national averages of $64,994 and $35,384, respectively.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2009, the median household income was $42,241 and the median income per capita was $25,707, compared to the national median income of $53,889 per household and $28,930 per capita.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2009, 23.7% of the population lived below the poverty line, compared to 13.5% nationwide.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In the 2020 census, 20% of Baltimore residents were living in poverty, compared to 11.6% nationwide.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Housing in Baltimore is relatively inexpensive for large, near-coastal cities of its size.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The median sale price for homes in Baltimore as of December 2022 was $209,000, up from $95,000 in 2012.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Despite the late 2000s housing price collapse, and along with the national trends, Baltimore residents still faced slowly increasing rent, up 3% in the summer of 2010.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The median value of owner-occupied housing units between 2016 and 2020 was $242,499.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The homeless population in Baltimore is steadily increasing.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The increase in the number of young homeless people was particularly severe.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2015, the life expectancy in Baltimore was 74 to 75 years, compared to the U.S. average of 78 to 80.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Fourteen neighborhoods, concentrated in East, West, and South Baltimore, had lower life expectancies than North Korea, and the figure in Seton Hill was comparable to that of Yemen.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2015, 25% of adults in Baltimore reported affiliation with no religion.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] 50% of the adult population of Baltimore are Protestants.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Catholicism is the second-largest religious affiliation, constituting 15% percent of the population, followed by Judaism (3%) and Islam (2%).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Around 1% identify with other Christian denominations.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2010, 91% (526,705) of Baltimore residents five years old and older spoke only English at home.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Other languages, such as African languages, French, and Chinese are spoken by less than 1% of the population.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Once a predominantly industrial town, with an economic base focused on steel processing, shipping, auto manufacturing (General Motors Baltimore Assembly), and transportation, Baltimore experienced deindustrialization, which cost residents tens of thousands of low-skill, high-wage jobs.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore now relies on a low-wage service economy, which accounts for 31% of jobs in the city.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Around the turn of the 20th century, Baltimore was the leading U.S. manufacturer of rye whiskey and straw hats.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] It led in the refining of crude oil, brought to the city by pipeline from Pennsylvania.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In March 2018, Baltimore's unemployment rate was 5.8%.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2012, one quarter of Baltimore residents, and 37% of Baltimore children, lived in poverty.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The city is home to the Johns Hopkins Hospital.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Other large companies in Baltimore include Under Armour, BRT Laboratories, Cordish Company, Legg Mason, McCormick & Company, T.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] A sugar refinery owned by American Sugar Refining is one of Baltimore's cultural icons.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Nonprofits based in Baltimore include Lutheran Services in America, Catholic Relief Services and Jhpiego.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Almost a quarter of the jobs in the Baltimore region were in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics as of mid-2013, a fact attributed in part to the city's extensive undergraduate and graduate schools; maintenance and repair experts were included in this count.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The center of international commerce for the region is the World Trade Center Baltimore, which houses the Maryland Port Administration and U.S. headquarters for major shipping lines.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Among all U.S. ports, Baltimore is ranked 9th for total dollar value of cargo and 13th for cargo tonnage.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2014, cargo moving through the port totaled 29.5 million tons valued at $52.5 billion.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Port of Baltimore generates $3 billion in annual wages and salary, supports 14,630 direct jobs and 108,000 jobs connected to port work, and in 2014 generated more than $300 million in taxes.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The port serves over 50 ocean carriers, making nearly 1,800 annual visits.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Among all U.S. ports, Baltimore is first in handling automobiles, light trucks, farm and construction machinery; and imported forest products, aluminum, and sugar.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Port of Baltimore's cruise industry, which offers year-round trips on several lines, supports over 400 jobs and brings in over $63 million to Maryland's economy annually.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore's history and attractions have made it a popular tourist destination.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] In 2014, the city hosted 24.5 million visitors, who spent $5.2 billion.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Much of the city's tourism centers around the Inner Harbor, with the National Aquarium being Maryland's top tourist destination.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] Baltimore Harbor's restoration has made it "a city of boats", with several historic ships maintained by the Historic Ships in Baltimore organization and open to the public.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p01] The Inner Harbor is also the home port of *Pride of Baltimore II*, the state's "goodwill ambassador" ship and a reconstruction of a famous Baltimore Clipper.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has historically been a working-class port town, sometimes dubbed a "city of neighborhoods".
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] It comprises 72 designated historic districts traditionally occupied by distinct ethnic groups.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Further inland, Mount Vernon is the traditional center of cultural and artistic life of the city.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] It is home to a distinctive Washington Monument, set atop a hill in a 19th-century urban square, that predates the monument in Washington, D.C. by several decades.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has a significant German American population, and was the second-largest port of immigration to the United States behind Ellis Island in New York and New Jersey.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Between 1820 and 1989, almost 2 million migrants—among them German, Polish, English, Irish, Russian, Lithuanian, Greek and Italian—came to Baltimore, mostly between 1861 and 1930.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] By 1913 the city was averaging forty thousand immigrants per year, until World War I closed off the flow.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] A Chinatown dating to at least the 1880s once held some 400 Chinese residents; a local Chinese-American association remains based there.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Beer making thrived in Baltimore from the 1800s to the 1950s, with over 100 breweries in the city's past.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The best remaining examples are the old American Brewery Building on North Gay Street and the National Brewing Company building in Brewer's Hill.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In the 1940s the National Brewing Company introduced the nation's first six-pack; its two most prominent brands were National Bohemian Beer (colloquially "Natty Boh") and Colt 45.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Both are still made today, albeit outside Maryland, and remain local staples whose "Natty Boh" mascot appears on merchandise throughout the area.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Each year the Artscape takes place in the city in the Bolton Hill neighborhood, close to the Maryland Institute College of Art.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Artscape styles itself as the "largest free arts festival in America".
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Each May, the Maryland Film Festival takes place in Baltimore, using all five screens of the historic Charles Theatre as its anchor venue.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Many movies and television shows have been filmed in Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] *Homicide: Life on the Street* was set and filmed in Baltimore, as well as *The Wire.* *House of Cards* and *Veep* are set in Washington, D.C. but filmed in Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has cultural museums in many areas of study.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Museum of Art and the Walters Art Museum are internationally renowned for their collections of art.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Museum of Art has the largest holding of works by Henri Matisse in the world.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The American Visionary Art Museum has been designated by Congress as America's national museum for visionary art.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The National Great Blacks In Wax Museum is the first African American wax museum in the country, featuring more than 150 life-size and lifelike wax figures.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is known for its Maryland blue crabs, crab cake, Old Bay Seasoning, pit beef, and the "chicken box" (chicken wings with french fries).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The city has many restaurants in or around the Inner Harbor, with Little Italy and Fells Point—home to the country's oldest continuously running tavern, "The Horse You Came in on Saloon"—drawing tourists and locals alike.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Public Market System is the oldest continuously operating public market system in the United States, and Lexington Market, dating to 1782, is among the longest-running in the world.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is also the last place in America with arabbers, vendors who sell produce from horse-drawn carts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 2015, Zagat ranked Baltimore second on a list of the 17 best food cities in the U.S.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore city, along with its surrounding regions, is home to a unique local dialect known as the Baltimore dialect.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] It is part of the larger Mid-Atlantic American English group and is noted to be very similar to the Philadelphia dialect.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The so-called "Bawlmerese" (named so for how locals often pronounce the city as "Bawlmore") accent is known for its characteristic pronunciation of its long "o" vowel, in which an "eh" sound is added before the long "o" sound (/oʊ/ shifts to [ɘʊ], or even [eʊ]).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] It adopts Philadelphia's pattern of the short "a" sound, such that the tensed vowel in words like "bath" or "ask" does not match the more relaxed one in "sad" or "act".
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore native John Waters parodies the city and its dialect extensively in his films.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Most are filmed in Baltimore, including the 1972 cult classic *Pink Flamingos*, as well as *Hairspray* and its Broadway musical remake.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has four state-designated arts and entertainment districts: The Pennsylvania Avenue Black Arts and Entertainment District, Station North Arts and Entertainment District, Highlandtown Arts District, and the Bromo Arts & Entertainment District.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Office of Promotion and the Arts (BOPA), the official city arts council, produces arts programs, manages several facilities, and coordinates major events such as the Inner Harbor's New Year's Eve and July 4 celebrations, Artscape, the Baltimore Book Festival, and the Dr.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Symphony Orchestra is an internationally renowned orchestra, founded in 1916 as a publicly funded municipal organization.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Its most recent music director was Marin Alsop, a protégé of Leonard Bernstein's.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Centerstage is the premier theater company in the city and a regionally well-respected group.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Lyric Opera House is the home of Lyric Opera Baltimore, which operates there as part of the Patricia and Arthur Modell Performing Arts Center.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Shriver Hall Concert Series, founded in 1966, presents classical chamber music and recitals featuring nationally and internationally recognized artists.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Peabody Institute, located in the Mount Vernon neighborhood, is the oldest conservatory of music in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Established in 1857, it is one of the most prestigious in the world, along with Juilliard, Eastman, and the Curtis Institute.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Morgan State University Choir is one of the nation's most prestigious university choral ensembles.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The city is also home to the Baltimore School for the Arts, a public high school in Mount Vernon nationally recognized for preparing students in music, theatre, dance, and visual arts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 1981, Baltimore hosted the first International Theater Festival, staging 66 performances of nine shows by international theatre companies; the event proved expensive and moved to Denver the following year.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In June 1986, the 20th Theatre of Nations, sponsored by the International Theatre Institute, was held in Baltimore, the first time it had taken place in the U.S.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has a long and storied baseball history, including its distinction as the birthplace of Babe Ruth in 1895.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The original 19th-century Baltimore Orioles (1882–1899) were among the most successful early franchises.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] A short-lived American League Orioles played in 1901–1902 before moving to New York and becoming the New York Yankees, while Ruth played for the minor-league Orioles, who competed locally until 1953.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The team currently known as the Baltimore Orioles has represented Major League Baseball locally since 1954 when the St.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 1995, local player (and later Hall of Famer) Cal Ripken Jr. broke Lou Gehrig's streak of 2,130 consecutive games played, for which Ripken was named Sportsman of the Year by *Sports Illustrated* magazine.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Six former Orioles players, including Ripken (2007), and two of the team's managers have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Since 1992, the Orioles' home ballpark has been Oriole Park at Camden Yards, which has been hailed as one of the league's best since it opened.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Before the 1950s, several attempts at a professional football team in Baltimore were blocked by the Washington franchise and its NFL allies.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The first major-league team in the city was the All-America Football Conference (AAFC) Baltimore Colts, which played from 1947 to 1949, joined the NFL for a single year (1950), and then went bankrupt.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 1953, the NFL's Dallas Texans folded.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Its assets and player contracts were purchased by an ownership team headed by Baltimore businessman Carroll Rosenbloom, who moved the team to Baltimore, establishing a new team also named the Baltimore Colts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] During the 1950s and 1960s, the Colts were one of the NFLs more successful franchises, led by Pro Football Hall of Fame quarterback Johnny Unitas.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Colts advanced to the NFL Championship twice (1958 and 1959) and the Super Bowl twice (1969 and 1971), winning all except Super Bowl III in 1969.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] After the 1983 season, the team left Baltimore for Indianapolis in 1984, where they became the Indianapolis Colts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The NFL returned to Baltimore when the former Cleveland Browns personnel moved to Baltimore and established the Baltimore Ravens in 1996.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore also hosted a Canadian Football League franchise, the Baltimore Stallions for the 1994 and 1995 seasons.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Following the 1995 season, and ultimate end to the Canadian Football League in the United States experiment, the team was sold and relocated to Montreal.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The first professional sports organization in the United States, The Maryland Jockey Club, was formed in Baltimore in 1743.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Preakness Stakes, the second race in the United States Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing, has been held every May at Pimlico Race Course in Baltimore since 1873.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] College lacrosse is a common sport in the spring, as the Johns Hopkins Blue Jays men's lacrosse team has won 44 national championships, the most of any program in history.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In addition, Loyola University won its first men's NCAA lacrosse championship in 2012.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Blast are a professional arena soccer team that play in the Major Arena Soccer League at the SECU Arena on the campus of Towson University.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Blast have won nine championships in various leagues, including the MASL; a previous Blast franchise played in the Major Indoor Soccer League from 1980 to 1992, winning one championship.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Other local clubs have included the semi-professional soccer sides FC Baltimore 1729 (founded 2018 in the National Premier Soccer League) and the Baltimore Bohemians, and Baltimore City F.C., an American Premier Soccer League club playing since 2023 at Utz Field in Patterson Park.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Blues were a semi-professional rugby league club that began competition in the USA Rugby League in 2012.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Grand Prix ran along the streets of downtown's Inner Harbor from 2011 to 2013, hosting the American Le Mans Series and IndyCar Series before being discontinued over scheduling conflicts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Marathon, the flagship of several races, begins and ends at Camden Yards, winding through neighborhoods including the Inner Harbor, Federal Hill, Fells Point, Canton, and Patterson Park.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Brigade were an Arena Football League team based in Baltimore that, from 2017 to 2019, played at Royal Farms Arena.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 2019, the team ceased operations along with the rest of the league.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has over 4,900 acres (1,983 ha) of parkland.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore City Department of Recreation and Parks manages the majority of parks and recreational facilities in the city, including Patterson Park, Federal Hill Park, and Druid Hill Park.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Gwynns Falls/Leakin Park, the city's most extensive park, is also the second-largest urban woodland in the nation.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The city is home to Fort McHenry National Monument and Historic Shrine, a coastal star-shaped fort best known for its role in the War of 1812.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] As of 2015, The Trust for Public Land, a national land conservation organization, ranks Baltimore 40th among the 75-largest U.S. cities.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is an independent city, and not part of any county.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] For most governmental purposes under Maryland law, Baltimore City is treated as a county-level entity.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The United States Census Bureau uses counties as the basic unit for presentation of statistical information in the United States, and treats Baltimore as a county equivalent for those purposes.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Hirsch Goldberg, a former press secretary for a mayor of the city, stated in the *Baltimore Sun* that because Baltimore is not in a county, there is no county-wide government that could assist the city, and that the city does not have as much political representation in the Maryland Legislature.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Goldberg argued that the status of not being in a county, along with the total square mileage, which he characterized as small, was damaging the city's fortunes.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has been a Democratic stronghold for over 150 years, with Democrats dominating every level of government.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In virtually all elections, the Democratic primary is the real contest.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] As of the 2020 elections, registered Democrats outnumbered registered Republicans by almost 10-to-1.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] No Republican has been elected to the City Council since 1939.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The city's last Republican mayor, Theodore McKeldin, left office in 1967.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] No Republican candidate since then has received 30 percent or more of the vote.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In the 2016 and 2020 mayoral elections, the Republicans were pushed into third place by write-in and independent candidates, respectively.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The last Republican candidate for president to win the city was Dwight Eisenhower in his successful reelection bid in 1956.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The city hosted the first six Democratic National Conventions, from 1832 through 1852, and hosted the DNC again in 1860, 1872, and 1912.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Brandon Scott is the current mayor of Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] He was elected in 2020 and took office on December 8, 2020.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Scott succeeded Jack Young, who became acting mayor in April 2019 and then mayor upon the resignation of Catherine Pugh, who left office amid a self-dealing book-sales scandal.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Pugh, a Democrat, had won the 2016 election with 57.1% of the vote.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Stephanie Rawlings-Blake, previously City Council President, became mayor in February 2010 upon Dixon's resignation and won a full term in 2011.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Sheila Dixon, Baltimore's first female mayor, had taken office in 2007 after Martin O'Malley became governor; she resigned in 2010 following an embezzlement conviction and an Alford plea to a perjury charge, as Maryland does not allow convicted felons to hold office.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore City Council is made up of 14 members elected from single-member districts and a council president elected at-large.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The council president is *ex officio* mayor pro tempore; if the mayor's office falls vacant, the council president ascends as mayor for the balance of the term.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Grassroots pressure for reform, voiced as Question P, restructured the city council in November 2002, against the will of the mayor, the council president, and the majority of the council.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] A coalition of union and community groups, organized by the Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now (ACORN), backed the effort.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore City Police Department is the primary law enforcement agency serving Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] It began in 1784 as a night watch and day constable system, was reorganized as a city department in 1853, and came under State of Maryland supervision in 1859.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Campus and building security for the city's public schools is provided by the Baltimore City Public Schools Police, established in the 1970s.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 2015, Baltimore agreed to pay $6.4 million to settle civil claims by the family of Freddie Gray, a sum greater than the combined settlements from 120 police brutality and misconduct lawsuits filed from 2011 to 2015.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has had a high violent-crime and homicide rate for decades, even as overall reported crime fell substantially from the mid-1990s to the mid-2010s.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Homicides peaked at 353 in 1993 and reached 344 in 2015, when the city recorded its highest homicide rate because its population had declined.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] After remaining above 300 annually from 2016 through 2022, homicides declined to 263 in 2023 and 200 in 2024.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is protected by the over 1,800 professional firefighters of the Baltimore City Fire Department (BCFD), founded in 1858 to replace the city's warring volunteer companies.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The BCFD operates out of 37 fire stations throughout the city.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Since the legislative redistricting in 2002, Baltimore has had six legislative districts located entirely within its boundaries, giving the city six seats in the 47-member Maryland Senate and 14 in the 141-member Maryland House of Delegates.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] During the previous 10-year period, Baltimore had four legislative districts within the city limits, but four others overlapped the Baltimore County line.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] As of October 2024, all of Baltimore's state senators and delegates were Democrats.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is split between two of the state's eight congressional districts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Most of the city is included in the 7th district, represented by Kweisi Mfume.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] A sliver of northern Baltimore is located in the 2nd district, represented by Johnny Olszewski.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] A Republican has not represented a significant portion of Baltimore in Congress since John Boynton Philip Clayton Hill represented the 3rd District in 1927, and has not represented any of Baltimore since the Eastern Shore-based 1st District lost its share of Baltimore after the 2000 census.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] It was represented by Republican Wayne Gilchrest at the time.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Maryland's former United States senator Ben Cardin is from Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] He was one of three people who, over four decades, represented the 3rd District—long including much of inner Baltimore—before election to the U.S.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Senate, the others being Paul Sarbanes and Barbara Mikulski.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Postal Service's Baltimore Main Post Office is located at 900 East Fayette Street in the Jonestown area.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The national headquarters for the United States Social Security Administration is located in Woodlawn, just outside of Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is the home of numerous places of higher learning, both public and private.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] 100,000 college students from around the country attend Baltimore City's 10 accredited two-year or four-year colleges and universities.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The city's public schools are managed by Baltimore City Public Schools.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Notable among them are Frederick Douglass High School, the second-oldest African American high school in the United States; Baltimore City College, the third-oldest public high school in the nation; and Western High School, the oldest public all-girls school in the nation.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore City College and Baltimore Polytechnic Institute share the nation's second-oldest high school football rivalry.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has a higher-than-average percentage of households without a car.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 2015, 30.7 percent of Baltimore households lacked a car, which decreased slightly to 28.9 percent in 2016.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore averaged 1.65 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore's highway growth has done much to influence the development of the city and its suburbs.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The first limited-access highway serving Baltimore was the Baltimore–Washington Parkway, which opened in stages between 1950 and 1954; its maintenance is split between the state of Maryland and the National Park Service, and trucks are restricted to its northern part.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Route 1 until Interstate 95 between Baltimore and Washington opened in 1971.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Interstate highways serving Baltimore are I-70, I-83 (the Jones Falls Expressway), I-95, I-395, I-695 (the Baltimore Beltway), I-795 (the Northwest Expressway), I-895 (the Harbor Tunnel Thruway), and I-97.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The city's mainline Interstate highways—I-95, I-83, and I-70—do not directly connect to each other, and in the case of I-70 end at a park and ride lot just inside the city limits, because of freeway revolts in Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] These revolts were led primarily by Barbara Mikulski, a former United States senator for Maryland, which resulted in the abandonment of the original plan.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] There are two tunnels traversing Baltimore Harbor within the city limits: the four-bore Fort McHenry Tunnel (opened in 1985 and serving I-95) and the two-bore Harbor Tunnel (opened in 1957 and serving I-895).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Until its collapse in March 2024, the Baltimore Beltway crossed south of Baltimore Harbor over the Francis Scott Key Bridge.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Planning for the Baltimore Beltway predates the creation of the Interstate Highway System.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Highways in the city are US 1, which bypasses downtown, and US 40, which crosses downtown from east to west.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Both run along major surface streets, US 40 utilizes a small section of a freeway cancelled in the 1970s in the west side of the city, originally intended for Interstate 170.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] State routes in the city travel along surface streets, with the exception of Maryland Route 295, which carries the Baltimore–Washington Parkway.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore City Department of Transportation (BCDOT) maintains the city's streets, sidewalks, and alleys, road signs, and street lights, and handles vehicle towing and traffic cameras.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Its responsibilities include the state and U.S. highways and the portions of I-83 and I-70 within the city limits; I-95, I-395, I-695, and I-895 are instead maintained by the Maryland Transportation Authority.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Public transit in Baltimore is mostly provided by the Maryland Transit Administration (abbreviated "MTA Maryland") and Charm City Circulator.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] MTA Maryland operates a comprehensive bus network, including many local, express, and commuter buses.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Charm City Circulator (CCC), a free shuttle bus service operated for the Baltimore City Department of Transportation, began running in the downtown area in January 2010.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Funded partly by an increase in parking fees, it provides free service seven days a week across four color-coded routes linking downtown with Johns Hopkins Hospital, Fells Point, Federal Hill, Harbor East, and Fort McHenry.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has a water taxi service, operated by Baltimore Water Taxi.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The water taxi's six routes provide service throughout the city's harbor, and was purchased by Under Armour CEO Kevin Plank's Sagamore Ventures in 2016.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In June 2017, the BaltimoreLink bus network redesign was launched.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The BaltimoreLink redesign consisted of a dozen high frequency, color-coded routes branded CityLink, running every 10 to 15 minutes through downtown Baltimore, along with changes to local and express bus service, rebranded LocalLink and ExpressLink.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is a top destination for Amtrak along the Northeast Corridor, and its Penn Station is one of the busiest in the country—ranked the seventh-busiest U.S. rail station as of 2014.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The corridor approaches from the south through the 1873 Baltimore and Potomac Tunnel, whose 30 mph (50 km/h) limit, sharp curves, and steep grades make it one of the NEC's worst bottlenecks, and from the north through the 1873 Union Tunnel.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Just outside the city, BWI Thurgood Marshall Airport Rail Station is another stop.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Scheduled Amtrak services include the *Acela Express*, *Northeast Regional*, and several long-distance trains such as the *Silver Star*, *Silver Meteor*, *Crescent*, and *Vermonter*.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] MARC commuter rail (the Brunswick, Camden, and Penn lines) connects Camden Station and Penn Station with Washington, D.C.'s Union Station and stops in between; the Penn Line added weekend service in 2013.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is served by two airports, both operated by the Maryland Aviation Administration, which is part of the Maryland Department of Transportation.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore–Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport, generally known as "BWI", is the main international airport in the Baltimore area.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] It lies about 10 miles (16 km) to the south of Baltimore in neighboring Anne Arundel County.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The airport is named after Thurgood Marshall, a Baltimore native who was the first African American to serve on the Supreme Court of the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In terms of passenger traffic, BWI is the 22nd busiest airport in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] As of 2014, BWI is the largest, by passenger count, of three major airports serving the Baltimore–Washington Metropolitan Area.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] It is accessible by I-95 and the Baltimore–Washington Parkway via Interstate 195, the Baltimore Light Rail, and Amtrak and MARC Train at BWI Rail Station.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is also served by Martin State Airport, a general aviation facility, to the northeast in Baltimore County.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Martin State Airport is linked to downtown Baltimore by Maryland Route 150 (Eastern Avenue) and by MARC Train at its own station.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has a comprehensive, signed system of unnumbered bicycle routes, with roads marked by bike lanes, sharrows, or Share the Road signs.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The network continues to expand, with over 140 miles (230 km) of lanes added between 2006 and 2014, and the city has also built bike boulevards, beginning with Guilford Avenue in 2012.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The city has three major trail systems—the Gwynns Falls Trail, the Jones Falls Trail, and the Herring Run Trail—the first two of which carry sections of the East Coast Greenway.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Protected cycle tracks on Maryland Avenue, Mount Royal Avenue, and Monument Street form the backbone of the downtown bicycle network, while the Stony Run Trail follows part of the old Ma and Pa Railroad corridor.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] A 2011 study by Walk Score ranked Baltimore the 14th-most walkable of the fifty largest U.S. cities.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The port was founded in 1706, preceding the founding of Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Maryland colonial legislature made the area near Locust Point as the port of entry for the tobacco trade with England.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Fells Point, the deepest point in the natural harbor, soon became the colony's main ship building center, later on becoming leader in the construction of clipper ships.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] After Baltimore's founding, mills were built behind the wharves, and the California Gold Rush brought orders for fast vessels.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] By the end of the nineteenth century, European ship lines maintained immigrant terminals there, and the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad made the port a major transshipment point.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The port has major roll-on/roll-off and bulk facilities, especially for steel handling.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Water taxis operate in the Inner Harbor.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Governor Ehrlich participated in naming the port after Helen Delich Bentley during the 300th anniversary of the port.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 2007, Duke Realty Corporation began the Chesapeake Commerce Center, a 184-acre (0.74 km2) industrial park on the site of a former General Motors plant in eastern Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The Port of Baltimore is one of two East Coast seaports with a 50-foot (15 m) dredge able to accommodate the largest shipping vessels.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has four water wheel trash interceptors for removing garbage in area waterways.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] One is at the mouth of Jones Falls in Baltimore's Inner Harbor, dubbed "Mr.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Another, "Professor Trash Wheel", was added at Harris Creek in the Canton neighborhood in 2016, with "Captain Trash Wheel" following at Mason Creek in 2018, and "Gwynnda, the Good Wheel of the West" at the mouth of the Gwynns Falls in 2021.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] A February 2015 agreement with a local waste-to-energy plant is believed to make Baltimore the first city to use reclaimed waterway debris to generate electricity.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In August 2010, the National Aquarium assembled, planted, and launched a floating wetland island designed by Biohabitats in Baltimore's Inner Harbor.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Hundreds of years ago, Baltimore's harbor shoreline would have been lined with tidal wetlands.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Biohabitats also developed a concept to transform a dilapidated wharf into a living pier that cleans Harbor water, provides habitat and is an aesthetic attraction.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Currently under design, the top of the pier will become a constructed tidal wetland.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Other projects to improve water quality include the Blue Alleys project, expanded street sweeping, and stream restoration.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Since 1985 the Wheelabrator Baltimore incinerator, formerly known as the Baltimore Refuse Energy Systems Co., has operated as a waste-to-energy incinerator.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The incinerator is a significant source of air pollution to nearby neighborhoods.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Several environmental groups, such as the Environmental Integrity Project, and the Chesapeake Climate Action Network, have been successful in advocating for reinforced pollution monitoring.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The incinerator is the city's single largest standing source of air pollution.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore's main media outlet since 2010 is *The Baltimore Sun*, which was sold by its Baltimore owners in 1986 to the Times Mirror Company, and then bought by the Tribune Company in 2000.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Since the sale, *The Baltimore Sun* prints some local news along with regional and national articles.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The *Baltimore News-American*, another long-running paper that competed with the Sun, ceased publication in 1986.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The city is home to the Baltimore Afro-American, an influential African American newspaper founded in 1892.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 2006, *The Baltimore Examiner* was launched to compete with *The Sun*.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] It was part of a national chain that includes *The San Francisco Examiner* and *The Washington Examiner*.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In contrast to the paid subscription *Sun*, *The Examiner* was a free newspaper funded solely by advertisements.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Unable to turn a profit and facing a deep recession, *The Baltimore Examiner* ceased publication on February 15, 2009.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Despite being located 40 miles northeast of Washington, D.C., Baltimore is a major media market in its own right, with all major English language television networks represented in the city.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] WJZ-TV 13 is a CBS owned and operated station, and WBFF 45 (Fox, with MyNetworkTV on DT2) is the flagship of Sinclair Broadcast Group, the second-largest station owner in the country.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Other major television stations in Baltimore include WMAR-TV 2 (ABC), WBAL-TV 11 (NBC), WUTB 24 (Roar), WNUV 54 (CW), and WMPB 67 (PBS).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is also served by low-power station WMJF-CD 39 (Ion), which transmits from the campus of Towson University.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Nielsen ranked Baltimore as the 27th-largest television market in 2009.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Arbitron's Fall 2010 rankings identified Baltimore as the 22nd-largest radio market.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Edgar Allan Poe lived in several different cities including Baltimore, which is where he died and was buried.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Several of his works were inspired and written during his time in the city including "MS.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Scott Fitzgerald—who had deep ties to Baltimore as a relative and namesake of Francis Scott Key—published the short story *The Curious Case of Benjamin Button*, about a man born in Baltimore who ages backwards.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Fitzgerald lived in the city for five years in the 1930s, partly so that Zelda could receive psychiatric care at Johns Hopkins and the Sheppard-Pratt Hospital; his first editor was the "Sage of Baltimore", H.L.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Anne Tyler has lived in Baltimore since the late 1960s and is known for her literary realism fiction that emphasizes family life.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] She has written a number of books set locally including *The Accidental Tourist* (1985), *Breathing Lessons* (1988), *Digging To America* (2006) and *A Spool of Blue Thread* (2015).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 1845, Frederick Douglass published his memoir: *Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass, an American Slave*.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Born on the Eastern Shore, Douglass arrived in Baltimore as a child.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] It is where he learned to read and write.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 2008, journalist, novelist and activist Ta-Nehisi Coates published his memoir of growing up in West Baltimore: *The Beautiful Struggle.* Coates writes of his challenging relationship with his father, troubled experiences in local schools and the street crime and drug epidemic of the 1990s.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Barry Levinson is a film maker and a native Baltimorean.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Several of his films pay homage to his upbringing in an immigrant family in the city: *Diner* (1982), *Tin Men* (1987), *Avalon* (1990), and *Liberty Heights* (1999).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Another Baltimore filmmaker, John Waters, began his career making experimental art films in the city including *Roman Candies* and *Mondo Trasho*.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] As his audience and film budgets expanded, Waters continued to set his films in Baltimore and to premier them at the Senator Theater.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Waters has continued to live in Baltimore and remains active in the local arts community.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The television representations of Baltimore often involve crime or law enforcement.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] From 1993 to 1998, the police procedural drama *Homicide: Life on the Street* aired with favorable reviews but low ratings.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Several episodes of the *X-Files* (1993–2002) took place in Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] *The Corner* (2000) is a mini-series based on a true story of people living amid the open air drug markets of West Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] The most known series set in Baltimore is *The Wire* (2002–2008), which was well-received and depicts the city as a war zone between drug trade and the police.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] In 2022, the limited drama series *We Own This City* premiered, starring Jon Bernthal and native Baltimorean Josh Charles.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has ten sister cities, as designated by Sister Cities International.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In Rome, Thorvaldsen made a name for himself as a sculptor.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Maintaining a large workshop in the city, he worked in a heroic neo-classicist style.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Upon his return to Denmark in 1838, Thorvaldsen was received as a national hero.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] The Thorvaldsen Museum was erected to house his works next to Christiansborg Palace.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen is buried within the courtyard of the museum.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In his time, he was seen as the successor of master sculptor Antonio Canova.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Among his more famous public monuments are the statues of Nicolaus Copernicus and Józef Poniatowski in Warsaw; the statue of Maximilian I in Munich; and the tomb monument of Pope Pius VII, the only work by a non-Catholic in St.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen was born in Copenhagen in 1770 (according to some accounts, in 1768), the son of Gottskálk Þorvaldsson, an Icelander who had settled in Denmark.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] His father was a wood-carver at a shipyard, where he made decorative carvings for large ships and was the early source of influence on his son Bertel's development as a sculptor and on his choice of career.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen's mother was Karen Dagnes (her surname is sometimes reported as Grønlund), a Jutlandic peasant girl.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] His birth certificate and baptismal records have never been found, and the only existing record is of his confirmation in 1787.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen had claimed descent from Snorri Thorfinnsson, the first European born in America.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen's childhood in Copenhagen was humble.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] His father had a drinking habit that slowed his career.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Nothing is known of Thorvaldsen's early schooling, and he may have been schooled entirely at home.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] He never became good at writing, and he never acquired much of the knowledge of fine culture that was expected from an artist.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In 1781, with the help of some friends, eleven-year-old Thorvaldsen was admitted to Copenhagen's Royal Danish Academy of Art (*Det Kongelige Danske Kunstakademi*), first as a draftsman and, from 1786, at the modeling school.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] At night he would assist his father with wood carving.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Among his professors were Nicolai Abildgaard and Johannes Wiedewelt, who are both likely influences for his later neoclassical style.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] At the academy, he was highly praised for his works.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In 1793, he won several prizes, from silver to gold, for a relief of St.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] He was consequently granted a royal stipend, enabling him to complete his studies in Rome.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Leaving Copenhagen on 30 August on the frigate *Thetis*, he landed in Palermo in January 1797 and traveled to Naples, where he studied for a month before making his entry to Rome on 8 March 1797.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Since the date of his birth had never been recorded, he celebrated this day as his "Roman birthday" for the rest of his life.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In Rome he lived at the Casa Buti, on the Via Sistina, in front of the Spanish Steps and had his workshop in the stables of the Palazzo Barberini.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] He was taken under the wing of Georg Zoëga, a Danish archeologist and numismatist living in Rome.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Zoëga took an interest in seeing to it that the young Thorvaldsen acquired an appreciation of the antique arts.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] As a frequent guest at Zoëga's house he met Anna Maria von Uhden, born Magnani.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] She had worked in Zoëga's house as a maid and had married a German archeologist.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] She became Thorvaldsen's mistress and left her husband in 1803.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In 1813 she gave birth to a daughter, Elisa Thorvaldsen.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen also studied with another Dane, Asmus Jacob Carstens whose handling of classic themes became a source of inspiration.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen's first success was the model for a statue of Jason; finished in 1801 it was highly praised by Antonio Canova, the most popular sculptor in the city.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] But the work was slow in selling and his stipend having run out, he planned his return to Denmark.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In 1803, as he was set to leave Rome, he received the commission to execute the Jason in marble from Thomas Hope, a wealthy English art-patron.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] From that time Thorvaldsen's success was assured, and he did not leave Italy for sixteen years.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] The marble Jason was not finished until 25 years later, as Thorvaldsen quickly became a busy man.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Also in 1803, he started work on *Achilles and Briseïs* his first classically themed relief.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In 1804 he finished *Dance of the Muses at Helicon* and a group statue of *Cupid and Psyche* and other important early works such as *Apollo, Bacchus og Ganymedes*.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] During 1805, he had to expand his workshop and enlist the help of several assistants.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] These assistants undertook most of the marble cutting, and the master limited himself to doing the sketches and finishing touches.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Commissioned by Ludwig I of Bavaria in 1808 and finished in 1832 a statue of *Adonis* is one of the few works in marble carved solely by Thorvaldsen's own hand, and at the same time it is one of the works that is closest to the antique Greek ideals.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In the spring of 1818 Thorvaldsen fell ill, and during his convalescence he was nursed by the Scottish lady Miss Frances Mackenzie.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen proposed to her on 29 March 1819, but the engagement was cancelled after a month.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen had fallen in love with another woman: Fanny Caspers.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Torn between Mackenzie and Anna Maria Von Uhden, the mother of his daughter Elisa Sophia Carlotta von Uhden Thorvaldsen, Thorvaldsen never succeeded in making Miss Caspers his wife.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Here he was commissioned to make the colossal series of statues of Christ and the Twelve Apostles for the rebuilding of Vor Frue Kirke (from 1922 known as the Copenhagen Cathedral) between 1817 and 1829, after its having been destroyed in the British bombardment of Copenhagen in 1807.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] These were executed after his return to Rome, and were not completed until 1838, when Thorvaldsen returned with his works to Denmark, being received as a hero.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Towards the end of 1843 he was prohibited from working for medical reasons, but he began to work again in January 1844.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] His last composition from 24 March was a sketch for a statue of the *genie* in chalk on a blackboard.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] At night he had dinner with his friends Adam Oehlenschläger and H.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] After the meal he went to the Copenhagen Royal Theatre where he died suddenly from a heart attack.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] He had bequeathed a great part of his fortune for the building and endowment of a museum in Copenhagen, and left instructions to fill it with all his collection of works of art and the models for all his sculptures, a very large collection, exhibited to the greatest possible advantage.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen is buried in the courtyard of this museum, under a bed of roses, by his own wish.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen was an outstanding representative of the Neoclassical period in sculpture.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In fact, his work was often compared to that of Antonio Canova and he became the foremost artist in the field after Canova's death in 1822.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] The poses and expressions of his figures are much more stiff and formal than those of Canova's.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen embodied the style of classical Greek art more than the Italian artist, he believed that only through the imitation of classical art pieces could one become a truly great artist.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Motifs for his works (reliefs, statues, and busts) were drawn mostly from Greek mythology, as well as works of classic art and literature.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] He created portraits of important personalities, as in his statue of Pope Pius VII.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen's statue of Pope Pius VII is found in the Clementine Chapel in the Vatican, for which he was the only non-Italian artist to ever have been commissioned to produce a piece.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Because he was a Protestant and not a Catholic, the church did not allow him to sign his work.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] This led to the story of Thorvaldsen sculpting his own face on to the shoulders of the Pope, however any comparison between Thorvaldsen's portrait and the sculpture will show that this is just a fanciful story built on some smaller similarities.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] His works can be seen in many European countries, especially in the Thorvaldsen Museum in Copenhagen, where his tomb is in the inner courtyard.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen's *Lion Monument* (1819) is in Lucerne, Switzerland.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] This monument commemorates the sacrifice of more than six hundred Swiss Guards who died defending the Tuileries during the French Revolution.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] The monument portrays a dying lion lying across broken symbols of the French monarchy.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] A replica of the Copernicus statue was cast in bronze and installed in 1973 on Chicago's lakefront along Solidarity Drive in the city's Museum Campus.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] A statue (Gutenberg Denkmal) of Johannes Gutenberg by Thorvaldsen can be seen in Mainz, Germany.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] The Thorvaldsen Museum is the museum in Copenhagen, Denmark where Bertel Thorvaldsen's works are displayed.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] The museum is located on the small island of Slotsholmen in central Copenhagen next to Christiansborg Palace.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Designed by Michael Gottlieb Bindesbøll, this building was constructed from public collection funds in 1837.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] The museum displays a collection of the artist's works in marble as well as plaster, including the original plaster models used in the making of cast bronze and marble statues and reliefs, copies of those works that are on display in museums, churches, and at other locations around the world.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] The museum also features Bertel Thorvaldsen's personal collection of paintings, Greek and Roman sculptures, drawings, and prints the artist collected during his lifetime, as well as personal belongings he used in his work and everyday life.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Outside Europe, Thorvaldsen is less well known.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] The Christus is also a feature of the visitors' center associated with the church's Rome Italy Temple, where it is displayed alongside Thorvaldsen's statues of the Twelve Apostles also from Vor Frue Kirke.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In the Paris France Temple it is an outdoor feature, placed in the courtyard.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Additionally, the LDS Church has historically used images of the statue in official church media, with this increasing with its use as a formal symbol, beginning in April 2020.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Additional replicas of the *Christus* include a full-size replica at the Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore, Maryland within its iconic dome, and a full-sized copy in bronze at the Ben H.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Powell III family plot in Oakwood Cemetery in Huntsville, Texas as a memorial to the Powell's son Rawley.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen's *Christus* was recreated in Lego by parishioners of a Swedish Protestant church in Västerås and unveiled on Easter Sunday 2009.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen's primary mastery was his feel for the rhythm of lines and movements.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Nearly all his sculptures can be viewed from any chosen angle without compromise of their impact.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] In addition, he had the ability to work in monumental size.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] Thorvaldsen's classicism was strict; nevertheless his contemporaries saw his art as the ideal, although afterwards art took new directions.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/bertel-thorwaldsen] A bronze copy of Thorvaldsen's *Self-Portrait* stands in Central Park, New York, near the East 97 Street entrance.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The **Dallas Museum of Art** (**DMA**) is an art museum located in the Arts District of downtown Dallas, Texas, along Woodall Rodgers Freeway between St.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In the 1970s, the museum moved from its previous location in Fair Park to the Arts District.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The new building was designed by Edward Larrabee Barnes and John MY Lee Associates, the 2007 winner of the American Institute of Architects Gold Medal.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The construction of the building spanned in stages over a decade.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The museum collection is made up of more than 24,000 objects, dating from the third millennium BC to the present day.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] It is known for its dynamic exhibition policy and educational programs.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Mayer Library (the museum's non-circulating research library) contains over 50,000 volumes available to curators and the general public.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] With 159,000 square feet (14,800 m2) of exhibition spaces, it is one of the largest art museums in the United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The museum's history began with the establishment in 1903 of the Dallas Art Association, which initially exhibited paintings in the Dallas Public Library.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Frank Reaugh, a Texas artist, saw in the new library the opportunity to display works of art.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] This idea was championed by May Dickson Exall, who was the first president of the Dallas Public Library.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The museum's collections started growing from this moment on.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] It soon became necessary to find a new permanent home.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The museum, renamed the Dallas Museum of Fine Arts in 1932, relocated to a new art deco facility within Fair Park in 1936, on the occasion of the Texas Centennial Exposition.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] This new facility was designed by a consortium of Dallas architects in consultation with Paul Cret of Philadelphia.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] It is still possible to visit this building.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In 1943, Jerry Bywaters, artist and Professor at Southern Methodist University, became the director of the museum, a position he held for the next twenty-one years.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Bywaters gave a sense of identity and community to the museum, acquired impressionist, abstract, and contemporary masterpieces were acquired, emphasized the Texas identity of the museum was emphasized.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] This identity is today represented by works by Alexandre Hogue, Olin Herman Travis, Bywaters himself, and others.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The 1950s proved a tumultuous time for the DMA and Bywaters, as a local movement arose to purge the museum of pieces by "communist" artists, such as Pablo Picasso, whose work was banned.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In 1963, the Dallas Museum of Fine Arts merged with the Dallas Museum of Contemporary Art, whose director for the previous four years had been Douglas MacAgy.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Rueppel became the director of the newly merged Museum.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The permanent collections of the two museums were then housed within the DMFA facility, suddenly holding significant works by Paul Gauguin, Odilon Redon, Henri Matisse, Piet Mondrian, Gerald Murphy, and Francis Bacon.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In 1965, the museum held an exhibition called *The Art of Piet Mondrian* and one entitled *Sculpture: Twentieth Century*.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] By the late 1970s, the greatly enlarged permanent collection and the ambitious exhibition program fostered a need for a new museum facility.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Under Harry Parker's direction, the museum was able to move once again, to its current venue, at the northern edge of the city's business district (the now designated Dallas Arts District).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The $54 million facility, designed by New York architect Edward Larrabee Barnes, was financed by a 1979 City bond election, together with private donations.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The project was galvanized by the slogan “A Great City Deserves a Great Museum,” and the new building opened in January 1984.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The DMA is part of the Monuments Men and Women Museum Network, launched in 2021 by the Monuments Men Foundation for the Preservation of Art.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] On June 1, 2022, a man named Brian Hernandez broke into the museum by using a metal chair to smash through the museum's front entrance.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] He damaged four pieces of art, including three ancient Greek vases that were over 2,000 years old.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The other item damaged was a ceramic bottle in the shape of a gar fish created by Native American artist.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In 2023, the museum announced that it had chosen the Spanish architecture firm Nieto Sobejano to lead a "reimagining" of its existing facility, with a budget estimated at between $150 million to $175 million.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The goals of the renovation are to expand gallery space, improve visitor circulation flow and accessibility, increase the museum's physical visibility and transparency, and redesign the museum's grounds.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The museum named Brian Ferriso, the current director of the Portland Art Museum, as its next director in 2025.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The museum's collections include more than 24,000 works of art from around the world ranging from ancient to modern times.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] They are conceived as a celebration of the human power of creation.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Objects in the museum's **African collection** come from West Africa and Central Africa.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The objects date primarily from the 16th to the 20th centuries, although the earliest object is a Nok terracotta bust from Nigeria that dates from somewhere between 200 BC to 200 AD.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Some works in the collection were created as symbols of leadership and status, while others express concepts related to the cycle of life.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Highlights of the collection include a Benin plaque of copper alloy over wood depicting a warrior chief, a carved wood Senufo rhythm pounder from southeastern Mali, and a Congo standing power figure studded with ritually embedded iron nails or blades.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The **American art** collection includes paintings, sculptures, and works on paper from the United States from the colonial period to World War II, and art from Mexico, and Canada.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Among the highlights of the collection are *Duck Island* (1906) by Childe Hassam, *Lighthouse Hill* (1927) by Edward Hopper, *That Gentleman* (1960) by Andrew Wyeth, *Bare Tree Trunks with Snow* (1946) by Georgia O'Keeffe and *Razor* and *Watch* by Gerald Murphy (1924, 1925).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] One of the most important pieces in the collection is *The Icebergs* (1861) by Frederic Edwin Church.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] This painting had long been referred to as a lost masterpiece.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The painting was given to the museum in 1979 by Norma and Lamar Hunt.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The Dallas Museum of Art also has one of the most thorough collections of Texas art.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] This is in great part thanks to Jerry Bywaters, director of the DMA from to 1943 to 1964, who was also one of the Dallas Nine, an influential group of Texas artists.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In addition to paintings by Bywaters, the DMA has works by Robert Jenkins Onderdonk, Julian Onderdonk, Alexandre Hogue, Clara McDonald Williamson, David Bates, Dorothy Austin, Michael Owen, and Olin Herman Travis.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The Dallas Museum of Art collection of **Ancient Mediterranean art** includes Cycladic, Egyptian, Greek, Roman, Etruscan, and Apulian objects.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Highlights of Egyptian art include a painted limestone *Relief of a Procession of Offering Bearers from the Tomb of Ny-Ank-Nesut* from 2575 to 2134 BC.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The more extensive Greek collection includes a marble *Figure of a man from a funerary relief* from 300 BC, bronze sculptures, decorative objects, and gold jewelry.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The art of ancient Rome is represented by a *Figure of a woman* from the 2nd century AD and a marble sarcophagus carved in high relief with a battle scene, c.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The museum's collections of **South Asian art** range from Gandharan Buddhist art of the 2nd to 4th centuries AD to the arts of the Mughal Empire in India from the 15th to the 19th century.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Highlights include a 12th-century bronze Shiva Nataraja and a 10th-century sandstone representation of the god Vishnu as the boar-headed Varaha.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The arts of Tibet, Nepal, and Thailand are also represented.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Many important artistic trends since 1945 are represented in the museum's vast collection of contemporary art, from abstract expressionism to pop and op Art, and from minimalism, and conceptualism to installation art, assemblage, and video art.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Contemporary artists within the collection whose reputations are well established include Jackson Pollock, Mark Rothko, Franz Kline, Jasper Johns, Robert Rauschenberg, Bruce Nauman, and Robert Smithson.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Among photographers represented in the collection are Cindy Sherman, Nic Nicosia, Thomas Struth, and Lynn Davis.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] When the current Museum facility opened in the mid-1980s, several artists were commissioned to create site-specific works especially for the Dallas Museum of Art: Ellsworth Kelly, Sol LeWitt, Richard Fleischner, and Claes Oldenburg with Coosje van Bruggen.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The expansive collections of **Decorative Arts and Design** feature over 8,000 works mostly from Europe and America in various media including furniture, ceramics, glass, textiles, and metalware.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Among the earliest works in the collection are 16th-century Spanish textiles, 17th century Chinese export porcelain, and European metalware, including the Hoblitzelle Collection of English and Irish silver.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Two exceptional early silver objects are a cup and cover (1742) by silversmith Paul de Lamerie and a massive wine cistern (1761–62) by Abraham Portal for Francis Hastings, the 10th Earl of Huntingdon.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] American 18th-century furniture forms the core of the Faith P. and Charles L.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Bybee Collection, featuring seating and case pieces from Boston, Connecticut, New York, Philadelphia and other regions.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The internationally renowned 19th- and 20th-century American silver collection is among the very finest of its type, with major examples by the leading firms of the last two centuries including Tiffany & Co., Gorham Manufacturing Company, Reed & Barton, and International Silver Co.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In addition to a unique solid silver dressing table (1899) made by Gorham for the Paris Exposition Universelle of 1900 other highlights include a Gothic Revival bed (c.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] 1844) made for Henry Clay, a Herter Brothers sideboard (c.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] 1881–82) for William Henry Vanderbilt, a pair of Louis Comfort Tiffany stained glass windows (c.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] 1885-95) depicting an undersea scene and a collection of Arts and Crafts movement and early modern designs by Gustav Stickley, Charles Rohlfs, Christopher Dresser, Louis Majorelle, Frank Lloyd Wright and others.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The contemporary design holdings include exceptional works by Ettore Sottsass, Zaha Hadid, Richard Meier, the Campana brothers, and a newly formed collection of jewelry.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Since 2014 is Carl Otto Czeschka's solid silver "Wittgenstein-Vitrine" a new exquisite part of the DMA-collections (1908, Wiener Werkstätte).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The Dallas Museum of Art's collection of **European art** starts in the 16th century.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Some of the earlier works include paintings by Giulio Cesare Procaccini (*Ecce Homo*, 1615–18), Pietro Paolini (*Bacchic Concert*, 1630), and Nicolas Mignard (*The Shepherd Faustulus Bringing Romulus and Remus to His Wife*, 1654).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Rosenberg collection brings an added depth to the museum's 18th-century French collection.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The 19th and beginning of the 20th century collection of French art also stands out.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The sculpture collection from the first part of the 20th century includes important works such as *Constructed Head n°2* by Naum Gabo, *Three men Walking* by Alberto Giacometti, 1936, *White Relief* by Ben Nicholson, and *Beginning of the World* by Constantin Brâncuși (1920).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The collection of works by Piet Mondrian is noteworthy, with works like *The Windmill* (1908), *Self-Portrait* (1942), and *Place de la Concorde* (1938–43).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The museum has significant holdings of **ancient American art**.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The collection covers more than three millennia, displaying sculptures, prints, terracotta, and gold objects.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Among the other highlights are gold objects from Panama, Colombia and Peru and the Head of the god Tlaloc (Mexico, 14th-16th century).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In 2008, the museum premiered the Center for Creative Connections (also known as C3), a 12,000-square-foot (1,100 m2) facility for interactive learning experiences.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The center presents exhibitions featuring the museum's collections and artists’ and community partners’ responses to them.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] Spaces include the Art Studio, Tech Lab, Theater, and Arturo's Nest.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In 2013, the Dallas Museum of Art instituted free admission and a free membership program.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In September 2015, Maxwell Anderson stepped down as director, and was succeeded by Walter Elcock, president of the DMA's board.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] In 2021, the museum returned a 10th century statue to Nepal where it was reinstalled in the temple from which it had been looted.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/dallas-museum-of-art] The museum lists 196 artworks on the Nazi Era Provenance Internet Portal.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Eponymous halls at both Berkeley and Hopkins pay tribute to his service.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] He was also co-founder of the Russell Trust Association, which administers the business affairs of Yale's Skull and Bones society.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Daniel Coit Gilman graduated from Yale College in 1852 with a degree in geography.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] At Yale, he was a classmate of Andrew Dickson White, who would later serve as first president of Cornell University.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] The two were members of the Skull and Bones secret society, and traveled to Europe together after graduation and remained lifelong friends.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman was also a member of the Alpha Delta Phi fraternity.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman would later co-found the Russell Trust Association, the foundation behind Skull and Bones.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] After serving as attaché of the United States legation at St.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Petersburg, Russia from 1853 to 1855, he returned to Yale and was active in planning and raising funds for the founding of Sheffield Scientific School.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman contemplated going into the ministry, and even obtained a license to preach, but later settled on a career in education.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] From 1856 to 1865, Gilman served as librarian of Yale College, and was also concerned with improving the New Haven public school system.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] When the Civil War broke out, Gilman became the recruiting sergeant for the Norton Cadets, a group of Yale graduates and faculty who drilled on the New Haven Green under the oversight of Yale professor William Augustus Norton.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] In 1863, he was appointed professor of geography at the Sheffield Scientific School, and became secretary and librarian as well in 1866.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Having been passed over for the presidency of Yale, for which post Gilman was said to have been the favorite of the younger faculty, he resigned these posts in 1872 to become the third president of the newly organized University of California, Berkeley.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] His work there was hampered by the state legislature, and in 1875 Gilman accepted the offer to establish and become first president of Johns Hopkins University.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Before being formally installed as president in 1876, he spent a year studying university organization and selecting an outstanding staff of teachers and scholars.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] His formal inauguration, on 22 February 1876, has become Hopkins' Commemoration Day, the day on which many university presidents have chosen to be installed in office.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Among the legendary educators he assembled to teach at Johns Hopkins were classicist Basil Lanneau Gildersleeve, mathematician James Joseph Sylvester, historian Herbert Baxter Adams and chemist Ira Remsen.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] In 1876, Gilman was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman's primary interest was in fostering advanced instruction and research, and as president he developed the first American graduate university in the German tradition.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] In 1884, Gilman was elected a member of the American Antiquarian Society.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman was also active in founding Johns Hopkins Hospital in 1889 and Johns Hopkins Medical School in 1893.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] He founded and was for many years president of the Charity Organization of Baltimore, and in 1897 he served on the commission to draft a new charter for Baltimore.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] From 1896 to 1897, he was a member of the commission to settle the boundary line between Venezuela and British Guiana.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman served as a trustee of the John F.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Slater and Peabody education funds and as a member of John D.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] In this capacity, he became active in the promotion of education in the southern United States.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] He was president of the National Civil Service Reform League (1901–1907) and the American Oriental Society (1893–1906), vice president of the Archaeological Institute of America, and executive officer of the Maryland Geological Survey.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] He retired from Johns Hopkins in 1901, but accepted the presidency (1902–1904) of the newly founded Carnegie Institution of Washington.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] His books include biographies of James Monroe (1883) and James Dwight Dana, a collection of addresses entitled *University Problems* (1898), and *The Launching of a University* (1906).
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] From 1902 he served (jointly with Harry Thurston Peck and Frank Moore Colby) as editor of *The New International Encyclopedia*.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] His first wife was Mary Van Winker Ketcham, daughter of Tredwell Ketcham of New York City.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] They married on December 4, 1861, and had two daughters: Alice, who married Everett Wheeler; and Elisabeth Gilman, who became a social activist and was a candidate for mayor of Baltimore, and for governor and senator of Maryland, on the Socialist Party of America ticket.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Mary Ketcham Gilman died in 1869, and Daniel Coit Gilman married his second wife, Elizabeth Dwight Woolsey, daughter of John M.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Woolsey of Cleveland, and niece of Yale president Theodore Dwight Woolsey, in 1877.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Daniel Gilman's brother Edward Whiting Gilman was married to Julia Silliman, daughter of Yale University professor and chemist Benjamin Silliman.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Daniel Coit Gilman died in Norwich, Connecticut.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] The original academic building on the Homewood campus of the Johns Hopkins University, Gilman Hall, is named in his honor.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] In 1897, he helped found a preparatory school called 'The Country School for Boys' on the Johns Hopkins campus.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Upon relocation in 1910, it was renamed in his honor and today, the Gilman School continues to be regarded among the nation's elite private boys' schools.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] On the University of California, Berkeley campus, Gilman Hall, also named in his honor, is the oldest building of the College of Chemistry and a National Historic Chemical Landmark.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Named for Gilman as well is Gilman Street in Berkeley.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman Drive, which passes through the University of California, San Diego campus in La Jolla, CA is also named for Gilman.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] The Daniel Coit Gilman Summer House, in Maine, was declared a U.S.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Gilman High School in Northeast Harbor, Maine, was named for Daniel Coit Gilman, who was active in local educational affairs, but it was later rebuilt and christened Mount Desert High School.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] He was awarded American Library Association Honorary Membership in 1895.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] The Papers of Daniel Coit Gilman were donated to Johns Hopkins University by Gilman's daughter Elisabeth, and are open on an unrestricted basis to the public at the Milton S.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Aside from many photographs of Gilman and his contemporaries, the papers include Gilman's correspondence with leading figures of the day, including Charles W.
[src:alfred-jacob-miller/daniel-coit-gilman] Du Bois, Booker T Washington and others.
